sentences: David Grisman (born March 23, 1945) is an American mandolinist.
His father was a professional trombonist who gave him piano lessons when he was seven years old.
In the early 1960s, he attended New York University.
When Grisman was 17 years old, he was invited on stage by Doc Watson to join him on mandolin for a rendition of “In the Pines”.
"Dawg Music" is what Grisman calls his mixture of bluegrass and Django Reinhardt/Stéphane Grappelli-influenced jazz as highlighted on his album Hot Dawg (recorded Oct. 1978, released 1979).

In the 1970s, he started the David Grisman Quintet with Darol Anger, Joe Carroll, Todd Phillips, and Tony Rice.
They released their eponymous first album in 1977 for Kaleidoscope Records and their second, Hot Dawg, two years later for Horizon Records, the jazz division of A&M Records.

In the 1980s, Grisman formed the record label Acoustic Disc, which issued his recordings and those by other acoustic musicians.
Grisman sued YouTube in May 2007, asserting in federal court that YouTube should be required to prevent individuals from illegally uploading recordings of his music.
The documentary Grateful Dawg (October 14, 2001) chronicles the friendship between Jerry Garcia and David Grisman.
He wrote much of the bluegrass music for the 1974 film Big Bad Mama directed by Roger Corman.
Acoustic Disc is an independent record label founded by Grisman in 1990.
